PS: Whaddya know, I found the article: <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.castersrealm.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=4231">eq.castersrealm.com/viewa...ticle=4231</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/usyllestraefv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Syllestrae FV</A> at: 6/21/02 6:17:59 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/utsensheng.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tsen Sheng</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/24/02 6:40:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2174.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Greenmist/Khukri Test of Pain</span><hr size=1> It amazes me that so many people are close minded when it comes to role play. I can think of many reasons why a softskin would seek to acquire Greenmist. A greedy little Gnome Shadowknight as myself would see such a weapon (It's not that great, but it is nice) as a valuable asset to his arsenal. If the softskin in question wanted to fool the Iksar into believing that they were an ally to be trusted, they could make every attempt to earn the trust of the Iksar.<br>
<br>
Here is an excerpt from the quest text:<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
You say, 'Hail, Librarian Zimor' <br>
<br>
Librarian Zimor says 'Hail, citizen, I hope that you are here to assist. We are gathering Crusaders to make an assault on the Libraries of Chardok. The slave creations have thrived in their sanctuary for too long. The tomes and texts they have stolen to fill their library belong us. They are even rumored to have a text on the Sacred Khukri of Rile, the Greenmist. If you see such a tome, you must bring it to me immediately. May Cazic-Thule guide you! <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
No where during the quest is Greenmist given away, it is in fact forged in the Grand Forge of Dalnir by the quester themselves. The Sarnaks have stolen the Greenmist Tome. It is very possible they planned on using it to recreate Greenmist and use it to their own benefit. Any Iksar could see the value of taking a powerful weapon out of the hands of the Sarnak, even if it meant that the weapon would be wielded by a softskin for a time. It would be far easier to betray a lone gnome and steal Greenmist back than to recover and reconstruct it themselves.<br>
<br>
After doing all the faction adjustments and Khukri quests, it is possible that &quot;an extremely harsh and xenophobic race&quot; just might trust an outsider to recover a relic such as the Khukri of Rile. Read the following and this possibility makes even more sense:<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Librarian Zimor looks disturbed as he examines the book. His hands tremble as he mouths the words on the ancient parchment pages. &quot;This book may alter the <br>
reality you see before you, Ooiioo, &quot;the scholar says as he continues to read the tome. &quot;The information that has been waiting in this book may have been brought to us by your hand, but your fate has obviously been chosen by our Lord. Our mystics have conveyed a new vision to us in this most recent season. Please take this note to Hierophant Oxyn, while I continue to translate this tome.&quot; the Librarian hands you a note and turns his attention back to the book. <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
It would seem that Librarian Zimor believes that the individual who had recovered and returned the tome was the one chosen to recover the blade. He refers to the recent visions of the Mystics as well. Religious fanatics often bend rules and ignore their own prejudices if it will further their own schemes.<br>
<br>
Obviously there are many more excuses one could use to explain their attempt at finishing the quest. It is however sad that instead of attempting to answer the original question, that people instead used this thread as an excuse to complain about someone completing a long and difficult quest. (far more difficult for a non-Iksar) If you have a problem with Verant, take it up with them. I always have and always will play the game as I see fit, not according to the wishes of others.<br>
<br>
